  "prompt": "Who investigates the Federal Bureau of Investigation?",
  "response": "The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) is subject to oversight and investigation by several entities:\n\n1. Department of Justice Office of the Inspector General (DOJ OIG): Conducts independent investigations of the FBI and DOJ operations.\n\n2. Congress: Through various committees, such as the House Judiciary Committee and Senate Judiciary Committee, which can conduct oversight hearings and investigations.\n\n3. U.S. Department of Justice: Provides overall supervision and can investigate potential misconduct.\n\n4. Internal Affairs (Office of Professional Responsibility): Investigates internal misconduct within the FBI.\n\n5. The Judiciary: Federal courts can review FBI actions and investigate potential legal violations.\n\n6. External Review Boards: Can be formed to investigate specific incidents or systemic issues.\n\nIf there are allegations of serious misconduct or constitutional violations, multiple oversight bodies might collaborate to investigate the FBI's actions.",
